[size=4][b]BetterBots — Bot Combat Abilities for Solo Play[/b][/size]

Aims to bring VT2-level bot ability usage to Darktide. Covers stance, dash, charge, shout, stealth, item-based abilities, and grenade/blitz with smart per-ability trigger heuristics.

Darktide has a complete bot ability system built into the behavior tree, but Fatshark hardcoded a whitelist that only allows two abilities. This mod removes that gate and injects the missing metadata so the existing infrastructure handles the rest.

[size=3][b]Why does this infrastructure exist?[/b][/size]

The bot ability system — behavior tree nodes, action queuing, ability extension — all work end-to-end in vanilla Darktide. So why did Fatshark build it and never turn it on?

[list]
[*][b]Vermintide 2 inheritance:[/b] Both games share the same engine. VT2 bots use career abilities ([url=https://www.vermintide.com/news/2018/12/17/dev-blog-how-bots-work-in-vermintide-2]dev blog[/url]) — the architecture carried over, but the ability-specific logic was never rewritten for Darktide's templates.
[*][b]Launch triage:[/b] Darktide launched in Nov 2022 in an unfinished state. In Jan 2023, Fatshark [url=https://www.shacknews.com/article/133824/warhammer-40000-darktide-launch-apology]paused all new content[/url] to fix crafting, progression, and stability. Solo mode — and bot abilities with it — was shelved from "final stages of testing" to "not a priority."
[*][b]Ability system redesign:[/b] The [url=https://www.playdarktide.com/news/dev-blog-class-overhaul]Class Overhaul (Oct 2023)[/url] completely reworked abilities, adding talent trees with 3 combat abilities per class. Writing bot heuristics for a system in flux would have been thrown away.
[*][b]Design philosophy:[/b] Fatshark wants bots as matchmaking placeholders, not capable teammates. A developer stated: [i]"It's easy to make great bots that can carry. It's hard to make average ones. But average is the goal."[/i]
[*][b]Server architecture:[/b] VT2 was peer-to-peer (host runs bots locally). Darktide uses dedicated servers — solo play requires local hosting with added performance cost, which was never implemented officially.
[/list]

BetterBots picks up where Fatshark left off: we populate the condition tables, inject the missing metadata, and add per-ability decision logic so the existing engine infrastructure can do what it was designed to do.

[b]Solo Play only.[/b] Darktide uses dedicated servers — mods cannot affect gameplay on Fatshark's servers. This mod only works when you host locally via the [url=https://www.nexusmods.com/warhammer40kdarktide/mods/176]Solo Play[/url] mod. It does [b]not[/b] work in public matchmaking or any other online mode.

[size=3][b]New in v0.9.0[/b][/size]

[list]
[*][b]Combat engagement leash:[/b] Bots no longer rubber-band back to the player mid-fight. Coherency-anchored melee leash extends engagement range when already fighting, under attack, pursuing ranged enemies, or after a dash/charge ability. Bots fight at their charge destination instead of turning around.
[*][b]Poxburster push:[/b] Bots now push approaching poxbursters at melee range — the standard human counterplay for instant kills.
[*][b]Mastiff-pounce priority:[/b] Bots prioritize enemies pinned by the Arbites cyber mastiff, helping finish off immobilized targets.
[*][b]Healing deferral:[/b] Bots defer health stations and med-crates to the human player when you need healing. Configurable threshold in mod settings.
[*][b]1.11.x compatibility:[/b] Fixed non-veteran bot profiles crashing on Darktide 1.11.0+ (Warband). Parser-level ability input validation fixes ability rejection on 1.11.x.
[*][b]Airlock crash guard:[/b] Prevents a vanilla crash at airlock doors when bot count exceeds teleport nodes (common with SoloPlay mods).
[/list]

[size=3][b]What works[/b][/size]

[b]Stance abilities (reliable):[/b]
[list]
[*]Veteran: Executioner's Stance / Voice of Command
[*]Psyker: Scrier's Gaze
[*]Ogryn: Point-Blank Barrage
[*]Arbites: Castigator's Stance
[*]Hive Scum: Enhanced Desperado / Rampage (untested — DLC required)
[/list]

[b]Dash / shout / stealth abilities (reliable):[/b]
[list]
[*]Veteran: Infiltrate (stealth)
[*]Zealot: Fury of the Faithful (dash), Shroudfield (stealth)
[*]Ogryn: Bull Rush (charge), Loyal Protector (taunt)
[*]Psyker: Venting Shriek (shout)
[*]Arbites: Break the Line (charge)
[/list]

[b]Item-based abilities (new in v0.3.0):[/b]
[list]
[*]Zealot: Bolstering Prayer (relic) — activates when allies need toughness
[*]Psyker: Telekine Shield (all 3 variants) — deploys under sustained fire
[*]Arbites: Nuncio-Aquila (drone) — launches when allies are hurt and enemies nearby
[/list]

[b]Grenade / blitz support (new in v0.6.0):[/b]
[list]
[*]All standard grenades: frag, krak, smoke, fire, shock, cluster, friend rock, flash, tox
[*]Zealot: Throwing Knives
[*]Arbites: Remote Detonation (whistle), Shock Mine
[*]Hive Scum: Missile Launcher (untested — DLC required)
[*]Psyker blitz: Smite, Chain Lightning, Assail
[/list]

[b]Smart trigger conditions:[/b]
Bots use per-ability heuristics to decide [i]when[/i] to activate — based on enemy count, threat level, health/toughness, distance, ally coherency, and corruption. Each ability has specific activate and hold rules grounded in community tactics. 15 of 18 trigger functions validated in-game (12 combat + 3 item); 1 N/A (cut content), 2 DLC-blocked.

[b]In-game settings and diagnostics:[/b]
[list]
[*][b]Ability categories:[/b] enable/disable stances, charges, shouts, stealth, deployables, grenades independently
[*][b]Behavior presets:[/b] Testing / Aggressive / Balanced / Conservative — controls how eagerly bots use abilities
[*][b]Feature toggles:[/b] bot sprinting, elite/special pinging, distant-special penalty, poxburster suppression, melee improvements, ranged improvements. Disable everything to revert to vanilla bot behavior.
[*]Bot ranged ammo threshold
[*]Human ammo reserve threshold
[*]Healing deferral mode and thresholds
[*]`Info / Debug / Trace` log levels
[*]Optional JSONL event log and `/bb_perf` runtime timing
[/list]

